## Conversation
User: 'In addition to removing the client-side dependency we should similarly
remove the server-side dependency on shared. We should effectively remove (or
move) the shared parts into each of the client and server.' This PR
(andrew/ts-v2-server-digest, on top of the client PR) does the server half of
the digest decoupling.

## Key insight
After the client moved to weave.trace.digest, grep showed weave.shared.digest +
weave.shared.object_class_util were used ONLY by the server (object_class_util is
imported only by digest). So they were already de-facto server-owned; moving them
into weave/trace_server/ is clean -- no client involvement, no new boundary edges.

## Actions
- git mv weave/shared/digest.py -> weave/trace_server/digest.py (fixed its
  internal import of object_class_util to weave.trace_server.object_class_util).
- git mv weave/shared/object_class_util.py -> weave/trace_server/object_class_util.py
  (no edits needed: it imports weave.shared.pydantic_util (foundation) + lazily
  weave.shared.interface.builtin_object_classes (the contract) -- both server->shared,
  allowed; NO client import, so no server->client violation).
- Repointed server importers (sqlite_trace_server, clickhouse_trace_server_batched,
  object_creation_utils, eval_results_helpers) + conformance/generate_fixtures.py
  from weave.shared.digest -> weave.trace_server.digest. ruff --fix re-sorted.
- Removed the digest re-export from weave/shared/__init__.py (grep confirmed no
  package-level importers) + updated its layout docstring.
- pyproject.toml: REMOVED the transitional 'Client must own its serialization
  (shared.digest)' contract -- the forbidden module no longer exists, and the
  structural contracts (client !-> trace_server, server !-> client, shared !-> both)
  now enforce the split physically. Back to 4 contracts.

## Why no new contract
The client cannot import weave.trace_server.digest (contract 1: client !-> trace_server);
the server cannot import weave.trace.digest (contract 2: server !-> client); shared
imports neither (contract 3). Physical separation + the existing contracts = stronger
guarantee than the temporary same-module forbid.

